  "text": "After it was observed that humans can hardly express their knowledge in distinct chunks, so that each chunk can somehow be transformed into a rule (or some other syntactically defined structure), which would then do \"the right thing\" in combination with an already existing expert system shell (e.g. EMYCIN), knowledge acquisition became recognized as \"a bottleneck in the construction of expert systems\" (Buchanan et al., 1983, p. 129) : Not the development of the original expert system (shell), but the acquisition of the domain specific rules for that shell turned out to be the tough part in building a fully functional system. Since some of an expert's relevant knowledge is tacit or implicit [CITATION_1] , experts cannot directly verbalize all relevant rules. Knowledge engineers therefore concluded that some special psychological method would be necessary in order to acquire the desired knowledge in the form that was needed for rule-based (or other) systems.",
